\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What is ROULADE?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ROULADE is an acronym.
 It stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ReasOnably UniversaL ADventure Engine,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a phrase which should roughly describe the intent of the game.
 ROULADE is a roleplaying game designed to support a wide range of different
 settings or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavors,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to use the standard parlance of the game.
 It is especially designed for those flavors in which there are a number
 of distinct power levels, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

layers,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which are nonetheless expected to interact.
 Its priorities can also be very well described both by the word itself,
 and by the words that make up the acronym, described as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
ROULADE 
\emph default
is a French word which roughly means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

to roll
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (such as one might do with dice in an RPG), and describes a dish composed
 of several layers rolled together and baked into a whole, just as each
 ROULADE 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is composed of multiple layers that describe the genre and the different
 players that interact within it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Reasonably
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Universal 
\emph default
means that while ROULADE aims to emulate most genres, it is not a one-size-fits-
all solution and in fact is likely not as good for some as it is for others.
 Nonetheless, the game still provides considerable flexibility and is thus
 hoped to be capable of emulating a wide range of different settings and
 game worlds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Adventure
\emph default
 is the chief aim of ROULADE: it aims to provide an experience suitable
 to worlds of high adventure and action, and not necessarily ones where
 a considerable deal of realism is expected or required.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Engine 
\emph default
is used here in similar fashion to the phrase 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

game engine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: in other words, it does not necessarily intend to provide a complete game
 out of the box (though many genres can probably be run with just this core).
 Instead, ROULADE's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Vanilla
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 flavor provides the basic tools and definitions on which other flavors
 can be built.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through these goals, ROULADE provides a flexible core with which to run
 anything from TV mysteries, to superhero action, to stompy mecha fighting
 giant monsters, and even to galaxy-spanning wars between gods and men alike.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Flavors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ROULADE handles the difference between different possible worlds and settings
 for the game with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavors.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Flavors define the standard names for the different layers within a setting,
 what specific character talents, powers, and training are available, how
 many points the players start with when making new characters, and may
 also define additional optional rules that further aim to emulate the genre
 and setting at hand.
 This book defines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vanilla
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 flavor of ROULADE: essentially a standard ruleset on which to build other
 flavors.
 Future books will describe other flavors in a wide variety of genres and
 settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Layers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the key features of ROULADE is the layer system.
 ROULADE flavors are often oriented towards settings with a number of distinct
 tiers or scales of power, which the game refers to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

layers.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Most games have three layers, but some that focus primarily on a specific
 power level might only use one, while others might add a fourth.
 The default rules of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Vanilla
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 use three, defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Vanilla
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(Va): This is the level of normal mortal human beings like you and I, all
 the way up to the pinnacle of natural human capability.
 Pulp detectives, masked vigilantes, and adventuring archaeologists are
 all examples of vanilla characters.
 Weaponry of this layer means basic guns, swords, and knives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Chocolate
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(Ch): This level is for those who are truly superhuman, whose abilities
 exceed what even the fastest or best human could on their own.
 Most superheroes fall into this category, as do many supernatural monsters,
 and this layer is also for things like tanks, planes, or mecha and their
 weaponry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Strawberry
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(St): This layer describes those who defy not just human limits, but whose
 power is among the best in the universe, beings who can threaten entire
 galaxies or lay waste to cities.
 Strawberry characters are seemingly invincible heroes and gods, galaxy-threaten
ing alien beings, and great titanic machines that stand as tall as skyscrapers
 and can level planets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within each layer, characters and objects have a variety of ratings that
 are rated from 1 to 8 and compared on the Universal Action Table to determine
 the difficulty of actions taken between characters on that layer.
 When dealing with relations between different layers, however, those numbers
 become irrelevant, and only serious training can overcome the difference
 in weight class.
 For the sake of ease of notation, ratings can be appended with the two
 letter abbreviation for their layer, such that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Vanilla 5
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Strength can simple be denoted with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Va5.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These layer names are used as a matter of convenience and neutrality, as
 befits the relatively generic nature of this core set of reference rules.
 Individual flavors of ROULADE may of course choose to describe them in
 more genre-specific terms.
 A superhero game might use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Vigilante, Superhero, Demigod
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 while a game of titanic monsters and robots might use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Human, Mecha, Kaiju.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Universal Action Table
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When taking an action, characters compare the relevant rating to that of
 the opposing character or a standard difficulty using the Universal Action
 Table.
 By cross-referencing the relevant ratings on the UAT, the character then
 finds their chance of success on a d100.
 If dealing with an opponent who is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

out of layer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the other hand, the character instead uses the column or row that indicates
 how far below or above the acting character's layer they are (indicated
 on the table as L +/- a number).
 If the character has any training relative to the action being taken, that
 will provide a bonus to the die roll, increasing their chance of success.
\end_layout

