\begin_layout Section
Using the d100
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ROULADE makes use of the d100, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

percentile
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 die.
 While dice of 100 sides do technically exist (the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Zocchihedron
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), they are of limited practicality, and as such it is far easier to use
 a pair of ten-sided dice (d10s) to generate a range of 100 values.
 One dice is designated as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 digit, and the other die the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ones
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 digit.
 You may wish to use different colored dice for each, and some ten-sided
 dice are available pre-printed with a range of 00-90 to serve as the 10s
 value.
 For the purposes of ROULADE, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

00
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 result is equal to 100, thus giving a range of 1-100 as possible results
 on the die.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Should the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roll low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 technique be unsatisfactory or deemed insufficiently intuitive for your
 group, an alternate method is possible.
 Rather than attempting to roll less than or equal to your chance of success,
 you may instead roll the d100 plus your chance of success, aiming to exceed
 a target number of 100.
 Note that when using this method, an equal-to result is no longer considered
 a success: this is necessary to ensure an equivalent mathematical result.
 
\end_layout

