\begin_layout Section
Concept
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every character should have some kind of basic concept.
 This is a simple descriptive statement or phrase that ideally describes
 what the character does, what their personality is like, and possibly what
 their goals might be.
 This concept can change later, but will provide a basis of inspiration
 on which to build them.
 Some examples might be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Brooding vigilante seeking vengeance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Noble paladin fighting for peace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fearless reporter looking for a big scoop
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Simple farmer forced to defend their home
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Heartless bounty hunter tracking a new target
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concept should of course suit the flavor and the campaign being played:
 you wouldn't necessarily play a star-hopping bounty hunter in a game about
 1930s street thugs unless that kind of sudden intrusion is exactly what
 your group is going for.
 Be sure to discuss your character concept with the GM and the other players
 so that you can work together to build a cohesive group from the start.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
SPECS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every character is defined by certain basic ratings, described by the acronym
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

SPECS,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Smarts, Psyche, Endurance, Celerity, Strength.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Each ability is rated between 1 to 8, and placed within a given layer.
 These stats are described as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Smarts
\emph default
: Measures the character's intelligence, knowledge, and perceptiveness,
 and is used for most mental actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Psyche
\emph default
: Measures the character's willpower, mental fortitude, and force of personality
, and is used for resisting mental attacks or making social actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Endurance
\emph default
: Measures a character's ability to withstand physical punishment and stress,
 and is used to resist most damage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Celerity
\emph default
: Measure's a characters agility, dexterity, and reflexes, and is used for
 many physical actions as well as avoiding attacks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Strength
\emph default
: Measure's a character's raw physical power and muscle tone, and is used
 for determining damage from melee attacks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each ability costs a certain number of points to buy at a given rating.
 These costs are summarized in the SPECS Cost table.
 Note that if the GM has a specific layer in mind for the game, you may
 not be able to buy out of layer, or may find yourself often outclassed
 (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

over
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-classed) if you do.
 Be sure to discuss your character concept with the GM and get permission
 when buying out-of-layer SPECS.
\end_layout

